<h1 class="title">Relation of S/sqrt(B) and the limit on mu</h1>
<p>
<b>Bottom line</b>: limit on mu scales as one over S/sqrt{B} ie: sqrt{B}/S
</p>

<p>
We know    \[\frac{S}{\sqrt{B}\]  and want to determine the corresponding expected stat-only limit on mu
Assume, the background is well modelled and we do not have significant sensitivity to signal ( \(D \sim B\)) .
</p>

<p>
We are Interested in the stat only limlit so we will ignore \(\sigma_B\)  and  \(\sigma_S\) .
</p>

<p>
The fitted signal is:
</p>

<p>
\(S = D - B \sim 0\)  with   \(\sigma_S = \sqrt{D} \sim \sqrt{B}\)
</p>

<p>
The fitted mu is 
</p>

<p>
\[\mu = \frac{D - B}{S}\]    with  \[\sigma_\mu = \frac{\sqrt{B}}{S}\]
</p>

<p>
The 95% CL on \(\mu\)  is  \(\sim 2 \sigma_\mu\) or  \(2 \times \frac{\sqrt{B}}{S}\)
</p>
